snippet.textDisplay:
You should continue tfs dbzAbridge, if you haven’t seen the original, tfs still does a really good job(especially later on) to recreate and almost completely remake the emotional and dramatic moments of the series in a faithful way.
(tho, i say especially later on, cus as you may notice, the saiyan saga[the first dbz saga] is a little raw from how old it is and how they where still trying to figure out their direction and style, its them starting out, and by the end of Frieza/Namek saga they have a really good grip in scripting,comedy,editing and voice acting... this movie was made around the middle of the Namek saga so it still has a bit of that old/“ slightly dated and inexperienced” feel to it, tho some of it can be attributed to the original material/movie,all im saying is that it gets a lot better.)

Having general knowledge of the plot helps, and there are a handful of deep cut jokes about dragon ball in general, but there’s still a lot to enjoy about it and it also makes for an interesting perspective.(where you are experiencing the series for the first time with their “dub” and interpretation of the characters and events that tfs as fans pay homage to)

Kimchi could help to explain a few details here and there(whenever its needed for more context), but honestly, while it is mainly a parody, they also faithfully represent the characters and learn to balance the comedy with storytelling more and more(so they explain things..all be it in their own “tfs” way most of the time)

All im trying to say is, don’t be afraid to just jump into the tfs abridge, i never actually watched dbz, and i find it really entertaining to first see the series through tfs’s lens.
